potuz: on a per-builder basis, and just repeat those values. From the point of view of the operator, it should be very simple to set these flags. You can just say, I want these flags for every builder, or I want this min-bid for every builder, or I don't set anything, and you just give me nice defaults for every builder.

169
00:36:47.520 --> 00:36:54.200
potuz: The unknown operator should only provide a list of builders that they trust, that they want to have contacted.

170
00:36:54.970 --> 00:37:14.270
potuz: So I think the complicated part of like having this per builder and having this configurable is either for a very advanced node operator or for someone that runs some keys of their own and some other keys, say for like Rocket Pool or Lido, and then they really need to have a separated list of keys.

171
00:37:14.300 --> 00:37:28.799
potuz: Yeah, defaults or configurations. But in general, I respect that node operators can just set one value and then the client fill the map with the pair builder values. It shouldn't be complicated for operators.

172
00:37:33.170 --> 00:37:48.180
Nico Flaig: Yeah, I mean, my concern is not really, like, if you can provide a file, this is all possible and easy to configure. But, currently, you can do it via the Key Manager API. Like, you can configure the validator client via that.

173
00:37:48.370 --> 00:37:55.210
Nico Flaig: And I think this n square n matrix, I mean, currently it's not supported, right?

174
00:37:56.040 --> 00:38:07.509
Nico Flaig: So we just need to make sure we come up with a design that also allows KeyManager API validator clients that only want to use that to be able to express the full config, basically.

175
00:38:17.590 --> 00:38:26.000
Parithosh Jayanthi: Where would you want external parties to provide the feedback to? Just in the PR, or what sort of feedback are you guys expecting?

176
00:38:26.000 --> 00:38:44.499
potuz: The FPR is good and it should be yesterday. We really need this to implement the builder path. We don't have an effective way of sending the signed auth without having this. So this should be like today. And parties should be staking pools mostly and builders because…

177
00:38:44.500 --> 00:38:46.240
Parithosh Jayanthi: Okay, so the explicit ask…

178
00:38:46.240 --> 00:38:47.399
potuz: Like, both of them.

179
00:38:47.400 --> 00:38:57.369
Parithosh Jayanthi: any staking pool, so Lido, Rocket Pools, everyone else, as well as any builder to provide feedback in, the Beacon API PR625, right?

180
00:38:58.210 --> 00:38:59.140
potuz: Yeah, perfect.

181
00:38:59.380 --> 00:39:09.020
Nico Flaig: Yeah, I would say in addition it should also be any DVT software because they need to aggregate the signatures to create the signed off request.

182
00:39:09.460 --> 00:39:15.720
Nico Flaig: So, I know, for example, that, Oball has issues if you put the pubkey in there.

183
00:39:15.920 --> 00:39:27.080
Nico Flaig: I haven't looked at the details of PODUS's PR, but yeah, that, maybe we should make sure we have all the details covered there, to also support dbt.

184
00:39:29.840 --> 00:39:32.049
Parithosh Jayanthi: Yes, that sounds perfect.

185
00:39:33.720 --> 00:39:41.460
Parithosh Jayanthi: Okay, thank you. Then please provide feedback on the PR, and then we can take any questions on Discord, Ether, and DSalvo.

