211
00:44:04.930 --> 00:44:16.769
Parithosh Jayanthi: The next item on the agenda was EPBS circuit breakers. We spoke about the fact that it will be client implementation specific.

212
00:44:17.030 --> 00:44:33.099
Parithosh Jayanthi: But we still did want to bring it up as to what, approach each client is gonna take, so that we have a brief discussion on it. Has any client already implemented their circuit breakers? What's the approach they will… they're going to take? What's the, status?

213
00:44:36.800 --> 00:44:46.889
Mehdi Aouadi: Yeah, we have an implementation on Teku. It's been reviewed. It's not been tested yet, but yeah, it's ready and would be ready for DevNet 7, I guess.

214
00:44:48.500 --> 00:44:52.850
Parithosh Jayanthi: And what's the approach you guys are using? So when does the circuit breaker trigger on Teku.

215
00:44:53.110 --> 00:45:03.980
Mehdi Aouadi: It's a little bit similar to the existing one, but it's based on the execution payloads, obviously. And basically, we have some options to define

216
00:45:04.180 --> 00:45:06.650
Mehdi Aouadi: A, monitoring window.

217
00:45:06.940 --> 00:45:16.439
Mehdi Aouadi: and some allowed consecutive missing execution payloads and a number of missing execution payloads during that window.

218
00:45:16.870 --> 00:45:34.640
Mehdi Aouadi: and it's also based on the builder index. Since the those indices can be reused. So we check if the builder index is we basically have a a a banning and unbanning logic based on the index.

219
00:45:34.920 --> 00:45:46.059
Mehdi Aouadi: And, we also check if, the, the public key associated to that index has been, updated, if it's the case, so we drop that ban, and, yeah.

220
00:45:51.120 --> 00:45:56.420
Nico Flaig: I don't really get what you do with the builder index. So you blacklist builders or?

221
00:45:56.590 --> 00:46:02.109
Mehdi Aouadi: Yeah, we have… we have a cache. Actually, we keep history of the, if a builder, for example, say.

222
00:46:02.120 --> 00:46:17.690
Mehdi Aouadi: didn't publish a execution payload for, say, 3 consecutive slots, we ban it for a couple of slots, and then we unban it. So we stop considering the bids from that builder, and we just look for the other ones.

223
00:46:18.740 --> 00:46:23.040
Nico Flaig: But it's not really a circuit breaker, right? So it's more like you…

224
00:46:23.040 --> 00:46:23.750
Mehdi Aouadi: Don't consider.

225
00:46:23.750 --> 00:46:24.680
Nico Flaig: So there are bits.

226
00:46:24.680 --> 00:46:29.949
Mehdi Aouadi: If that's the case, we fall back to the self-building process.

227
00:46:32.760 --> 00:46:36.819
Nico Flaig: So if your circuit breaker is triggered, you only self build, or.

228
00:46:37.590 --> 00:46:45.830
Mehdi Aouadi: Yeah, if if if if the circuit breaker is triggered, we we fall back to the we ban that builder, and we fall back to the self building.

229
00:46:49.710 --> 00:46:57.050
Nico Flaig: Okay, it's pretty much what I have in Lodestar as well. So it's we. I kept it pretty similar to what we had pre-close.

230
00:46:57.440 --> 00:47:12.780
Nico Flaig: the only factor, I guess, is you consider payloads instead of blocks, and then I scale the fault inspection window on a… yeah, right, I scale it, if blocks are missed, so I'm not, counting those, but…

231
00:47:13.170 --> 00:47:15.709
Nico Flaig: It's a bit more complex, but not by much.

232
00:47:16.600 --> 00:47:24.319
Mehdi Aouadi: Yeah, it's basically the same logic. We just have that builder index consideration in addition to the block logic we had.

233
00:47:43.060 --> 00:47:49.319
Parithosh Jayanthi: That sounds good. Prysm or potuz, do you want to talk about your approach?

234
00:47:54.230 --> 00:48:06.739
potuz: So I forgot to bring the full document. I think we want to have something quite complicated, or at least a bit more involved, in which we will allow the operator

235
00:48:06.740 --> 00:48:15.789
potuz: to set different parameters to what are the payloads that, what are the parameters on payloads that he'll like to have them banned.

236
00:48:16.390 --> 00:48:27.789
potuz: So we want to have fallback mechanisms in which we fall back to trusted builders or we fall back to P2P builders.

237
00:48:27.840 --> 00:48:40.040
potuz: So… so there's… there's different scenarios in which we want to… I… to fall back to… I've actually trusted builders instead of, P2P builders, because the P2P builders can be civil attacked.

238
00:48:40.530 --> 00:48:48.910
potuz: So I promise I'll have a full document written down with all the options. We discussed this in Svalbard. We found a lot of bugs.

239
00:48:49.040 --> 00:48:59.619
potuz: on the original approach that we wanted to fall back to P2P, but P2P can be easily civil attacked, and cheaply now, civil attacked, so to… to land a lot of empty blocks.

240
00:48:59.890 --> 00:49:15.900
potuz: So what we want to do is to have a fallback mechanism in which if we see many blocks that are missing, fall back only to trusted builders. And if we see payloads that are missing from our trusted builders, then fall back to self-building.

241
00:49:16.530 --> 00:49:17.490
potuz: Yeah.

242
00:49:18.220 --> 00:49:23.159
potuz: Anyways, I'll promise I'll have something written down complete in the next few days.

243
00:49:24.570 --> 00:49:26.699
Parithosh Jayanthi: Okay, that sounds awesome.

244
00:49:30.990 --> 00:49:32.790
Parithosh Jayanthi: Tony had a question?

245
00:49:32.790 --> 00:49:33.170
potuz: Yeah, I.

246
00:49:33.170 --> 00:49:33.689
Parithosh Jayanthi: Yeah, so true.

247
00:49:33.690 --> 00:49:44.160
potuz: To answer to Tony, so the problem with P2P is that today is very cheap. I mean, we can argue that this is part of the protocol itself.

248
00:49:44.570 --> 00:49:52.489
potuz: But today, before Gloas, if a builder wants to, like, flood the network with empty blocks.

249
00:49:52.680 --> 00:50:03.219
potuz: they could do it. You could pay, you could bid, and you can win the bid, and you will just make a liveness province on Ethereum. You will make, including blocks, very expensive. You're gonna have to,

250
00:50:03.620 --> 00:50:04.909
potuz: Win their bid.

251
00:50:06.010 --> 00:50:10.129
potuz: The relay presumably is going to stop this from happening.

252
00:50:10.530 --> 00:50:11.660
potuz: But…

253
00:50:11.920 --> 00:50:21.059
potuz: on a situation where we have these P2P bids, and the blocks are so cheap as they are now, someone can just, like, bid them over P2P and win.

254
00:50:21.210 --> 00:50:35.109
potuz: and prevent blocks from being included. Again, this is part of the open market we have. In principle, you could accept this, but I think clients can try to prevent this from happening. If we see lots of blocks that are missing, stop.

255
00:50:35.200 --> 00:50:45.139
potuz: P2P bids. If we don't recognize the builders, we don't recognize the builder IDs, then we can just, like, stop taking bids from P2P, for example.

256
00:50:48.360 --> 00:50:53.000
Toni Wahrstätter: Thanks. Is there a difference between the execution payment and the trustless payment?

257
00:50:54.190 --> 00:51:01.340
potuz: So the execution payment doesn't really matter over P2P. Over P2P, we don't allow execution payments.

258
00:51:01.880 --> 00:51:06.229
potuz: And I think this is not an issue about payments itself, it's just an issue about

259
00:51:06.460 --> 00:51:15.260
potuz: I can just pin up a thousand keys over P2P. If one of them gets spammed, I'm just gonna send bits on the other key.

260
00:51:15.320 --> 00:51:33.669
potuz: And to answer to Nikos, trusted builders are builders that are working today. Their liveness of the chain today depends on them. If they are not buggy, and if they are working, I think it's better to rely on them before relying on local building. Trusted builders

261
00:51:33.780 --> 00:51:41.359
potuz: have been resilient, and they are providing us blocks today that are better blocks than if we fall back to local building.

262
00:51:41.760 --> 00:51:43.419
potuz: We like it or not.

263
00:51:43.880 --> 00:51:50.000
potuz: trusted blocks are better than the blocks that my Nuke provides or builds.

264
00:51:52.240 --> 00:52:03.950
Nico Flaig: Yeah, I just wanted to… so we clarified it. So the… basically the issue with falling back to only local would be basically a liveness issue for a lot of DeFi apps, I guess?

265
00:52:04.170 --> 00:52:07.950
Nico Flaig: So so that is the argument. Right? Just to clarify that.

266
00:52:07.950 --> 00:52:12.350
potuz: Yeah, but also like checking on the health of trusted.

267
00:52:12.490 --> 00:52:22.749
potuz: builders, it's very easy now on Gloas, because I don't need to be the proposer. I can just see that Titan is not producing blocks, and I can just blacklist Titan immediately.

268
00:52:23.250 --> 00:52:30.400
potuz: So it's the easy part is blacklisting the trusted builders. The hard part is blacklisting the P. 2 P. Builders.

269
00:53:00.610 --> 00:53:04.169
Parithosh Jayanthi: Do we want to move the discussion from chat to the call?

270
00:53:04.600 --> 00:53:10.499
potuz: Yeah, so Dima is asking, what about this execution flag that we have this value on the bid?

271
00:53:10.630 --> 00:53:15.579
potuz: And yes, there is no reason to have that value on the bid.

272
00:53:15.690 --> 00:53:23.480
potuz: I think it was included just for accountability reasons, so that anyone can actually check In principle, you could

273
00:53:23.490 --> 00:53:36.030
potuz: Check that there is a transaction that pays that much to the fee recipient in the payload. And this is an option that is there because that value is on the bid on the CL block.

274
00:53:36.030 --> 00:53:48.349
potuz: But we don't enforce anything on the CL, we just have that value and provide it as an option. That value is there, and it's completely ignored. The only check that we do is that that value is zero for P2P bits.

275
00:53:51.070 --> 00:53:53.429
Dima Gusakov | Lido: I mean, what I'm trying to say is that

276
00:53:54.130 --> 00:54:11.519
Dima Gusakov | Lido: like, right now, you do have this trusted part, and there is a transaction with some amount. However, there are no signs on-chain about what this value should be. When you are now adding this field, and you're saying, okay, for

277
00:54:12.070 --> 00:54:29.200
Dima Gusakov | Lido: trustless payments for P2P bids, this value should be zero, but for trusted bids, it would likely mean nothing, and it might confuse, I don't know, an external observer, if this value is, for example, is incorrect.

278
00:54:29.370 --> 00:54:36.700
Dima Gusakov | Lido: So you will have a record on chain saying that for this payload, the EL payment was, I don't know, 1 ETH.

279
00:54:36.810 --> 00:54:46.379
Dima Gusakov | Lido: But then there is no transaction within a block, which would be misleading for the external observer, which would see that, oh, this is a field that is written on-chain.

280
00:54:46.690 --> 00:54:54.329
Dima Gusakov | Lido: But it's never validated, so… I'm pretty much confused about why do we even need this value.

281
00:54:54.330 --> 00:55:01.629
potuz: It is an off protocol field. An external observer can either ignore it or try to validate it itself.

282
00:55:02.120 --> 00:55:10.960
potuz: If you don't have it, then, well, you don't even have the information of what that builder promised to pay.

283
00:55:17.910 --> 00:55:18.860
Dima Gusakov | Lido: Okay, but…

284
00:55:19.330 --> 00:55:27.239
Dima Gusakov | Lido: Like right now, the only way how you know what, what Builder promised you to pay is your negotiation with the relay.

285
00:55:28.300 --> 00:55:41.230
Dima Gusakov | Lido: And, now you have this… like, how this value helps. So would now… would builders now propagate the bids of this standard format over the… across relays as well? Or would they just…

286
00:55:41.360 --> 00:55:46.239
Dima Gusakov | Lido: act in a way they act right now, when you cannot distinguish a

287
00:55:46.820 --> 00:55:55.030
Dima Gusakov | Lido: builder block from a locally built block from the on-chain data, because from the on-chain perspective, it's just a self-built block.

288
00:55:55.030 --> 00:56:00.819
potuz: would identify an externally built block. So the way this works is I contact Titan.

289
00:56:01.010 --> 00:56:13.640
potuz: And Titan replies to me with a bid, and this bid would tell me the trusted part, the trustless part of the bid is zero, or it could be like one way, and the trusted part is 2ETH.

290
00:56:13.930 --> 00:56:23.469
potuz: And if I trust Titan, I would just consider those two ETH as part of a payment. Then I contact some random guy that just opens an endpoint.

291
00:56:23.500 --> 00:56:35.799
potuz: And I contact him because, well, I just want to get more bids fast. And then to that random guy, I would add a flag that says the max trusted bid that I take from that builder is zero.

292
00:56:36.060 --> 00:56:52.869
potuz: So this random guy would just receive my call, it would know that I take zero trusted bits from them, and then they will put, say, I give you 0.5 ETH on the trustless payment, and zero on the trusted part, and then I just evaluate, do I want to have

293
00:56:52.870 --> 00:57:05.319
potuz: from this random guy, half an ETH that I'm sure to receive, or do I want to have one ETH from Titan that I don't know if I'm gonna receive, I trust that they're gonna pay me on the EL, and then I just put whatever bid I want.

294
00:57:05.520 --> 00:57:09.969
potuz: But this is the negotiation happens directly with both of them.

295
00:57:10.110 --> 00:57:21.560
potuz: If there are relays, and those relays want to be dealing with these things, I mean, again, this is part of the protocol, and the client would only deal with the relay as if it were a builder.

296
00:57:23.990 --> 00:57:41.800
Dima Gusakov | Lido: Yeah, okay, that's understood. I'm trying to understand what stops builders from keeping their operations in the way they do now when instead of propagating a bit, they only propagate a header and then the node just accepts this and pretends that that was a self-built block.

297
00:57:42.510 --> 00:57:46.889
potuz: Oh, we… you don't… you can't, you need to sign it. So, if the…

298
00:57:47.050 --> 00:58:01.399
potuz: I mean, that includes, like, adding a lot of support on codebases that at least Prysm would not do, I understand Lodestar would also not do, and I suspect no client would support that. To have that sort of, like, dealing, it would be the following.

299
00:58:01.400 --> 00:58:08.620
potuz: the… I would need to contact directly a builder, or a relay, or whatever it is. You would need to send me a blinded execution payload bid.

300
00:58:09.030 --> 00:58:12.490
potuz: That I will sign myself as a self-built.

301
00:58:12.790 --> 00:58:27.380
potuz: the value of the trusted bid is going to be zero, because we, on self-built blocks, we just put zero for the value of the payment, and then we will just arrange for a payment off protocol somewhere. I will sign the bid as if it was self-built.

302
00:58:27.380 --> 00:58:38.889
potuz: And then again, we will have to have another conversation when the payload needs to be propagated. I need to get a blinded envelope that I need to sign as if I built it myself, and then send it.

303
00:58:39.050 --> 00:58:43.970
potuz: So all of this mechanism, I don't think, is going to be supported by clients.

304
00:58:44.960 --> 00:58:49.769
potuz: It's possible to do, if you for clients, and you do this, and such a market,

305
00:58:49.900 --> 00:58:53.529
potuz: develops. It's something that we cannot prevent.

306
00:58:54.580 --> 00:59:09.640
Dima Gusakov | Lido: Okay, and why don't we just take one step forward and somehow validate that there is a transaction with like to fee recipient with the corresponding EL payment so that this value would finally become something.

307
00:59:09.640 --> 00:59:10.030
potuz: That's.

308
00:59:10.030 --> 00:59:10.410
Dima Gusakov | Lido: For me.

309
00:59:10.410 --> 00:59:35.240
potuz: That makes it just too complicated for no reason. And it's also attackable because there could be a transaction and there could be like two. We could validate, for example, on the EL that the balance on the fee recipient was increased, but then the transaction itself on the builder could be involved, could be taken from several sources. Someone could actually send money to the fee recipient, like making the balance increase in a complicated manner.

310
00:59:35.240 --> 00:59:47.069
potuz: This adds a lot of complexity and interactions between the CL and the EL that seems completely unnecessary. If you are an involved player and you really care about validating this, I presume that you could do this off-chain.

311
00:59:48.860 --> 00:59:50.579
Dima Gusakov | Lido: Okay, gotcha. Thank you.

312
01:00:02.000 --> 01:00:06.080
Parithosh Jayanthi: Okay, thanks. Any other follow-up questions for the topic?

313
01:00:11.930 --> 01:00:18.870
Parithosh Jayanthi: Okay, I guess next step would be, potuz passing the document which defines how their,

